               <interp inst="t18291029-196" type="year" value="1829"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18291029-196" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18291029"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18291029-196" type="date" value="18291029"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18291029-196-off1100-c1299" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-196-defend1608 t18291029-196-off1100 t18291029-196-verdict1105"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18291029-196-off1102-c1301" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-196-defend1611 t18291029-196-off1102 t18291029-196-verdict1107"></join>
         
               <p>Before Mr. Sergeant 
               <persName id="t18291029-196-person1607">Arabin</persName>
            .</p>
               <p>2038. 
               <persName id="t18291029-196-defend1608" type="defendantName">
                  JANE 
                  BAIN
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-defend1608" type="surname" value="BAIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-defend1608" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-defend1608" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-defend1608" type="age" value="37"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was indicted for <rs id="t18291029-196-off1100" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-off1100" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-off1100" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18291029-196-cd1101" type="crimeDate">19th of September</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-196-off1100 t18291029-196-cd1101"></join>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-196-off1102 t18291029-196-cd1101"></join>, 49 prints, value 40s.
            </rs>, the goods of 
               <persName id="t18291029-196-victim1609" type="victimName">
                  Henry 
                  Triggs
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-victim1609" type="surname" value="Triggs"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-victim1609" type="given" value="Henry"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-victim1609" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; and 
               
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-defend1611" type="defendantName">
                     ROBERT 
                     SIMPSON
                  <interp inst="t18291029-196-defend1611" type="surname" value="SIMPSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-defend1611" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-defend1611" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18291029-196-off1102" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-off1102" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-off1102" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp>
               feloniously receiving part of the said prints, well knowing them to have been stolen
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>TWO OTHER COUNTS, stating them to be the goods of 
               <persName id="t18291029-196-victim1612" type="victimName">
                  Thomas Norton 
                  Longman
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-victim1612" type="surname" value="Longman"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-victim1612" type="given" value="Thomas Norton"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-victim1612" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and other persons.</p>
               <p>MESSRS. BOLLAND and CRESWELL conducted the prosecution.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1613">
                  HENRY 
                  TRIGGS
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1613" type="surname" value="TRIGGS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1613" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1613" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18291029-196-viclabel1103" type="occupation">copper-plate printer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-196-victim1609 t18291029-196-viclabel1103"></join>, employed by Messrs. Longman, Rees and Co., Westley and Co., and Mr. Marshall, to take impressions from steel plates for the forthcoming annuals, the Friendship's Offering, the Gem, the Literary Souvenir, and the Juvenile Forget Me Not; I was employed first about June last - the respective proprietors find paper for those plates: I had struck off impressions from them all, previous to the 19th of September, but never gave any of them out of my custody. The female prisoner was in my employ, as <rs id="t18291029-196-deflabel1104" type="occupation">servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-196-defend1608 t18291029-196-deflabel1104"></join>, and had been so about six weeks previous to her apprehension - I gave her a positive injunction when she came into my service not to touch the prints; on the 18th or 19th of September she was taken into custody - it was on a Thursday; I accused her of stealing the prints - she said she was very sorry, that she had given them to her mother for her youngest brother, and her mother was a very wicked bad woman to sell them - I do not recollect her saying how many she had taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182910290078"></xptr>COURT. Q. Did you say they had been sold? A. I said she had almost ruined me by giving these prints to her mother, and their being exposed for public sale, as it would show I was not a trustworthy person; I could not ascertain how many I had lost - we have an immense quantity, and it would be impossible to detect one or two dozen - at that time none ought to have been issued to the public - I had delivered some of the Juvenile Forget Me Not to Messrs. Westley and Davis.</p>
               <p>MR. CRESWELL. Q. Had you any right to any of them yourself? A. According to the custom of the trade we consider ourselves entitled to one or two impressions, not more.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. LEE. Q. I believe you were suspected of having parted with them? A. Yes, at first: after the examination at the office I asked Simpson how he came by the prints, and he said an elderly woman with a child sold them to him - he asked me if there was any one I suspected about my house; I said I could not possibly suspect any one of my work-people; at my suggestion he went willingly to my house, to see if he could point out the person who sold them - he said it was not my female servant; it struck me it might probably be her mother - we went to her mother's in London-street; he knocked, and I staid outside - her mother came to the door, and he told me that was the woman; I had parted with some of them to Messrs. Westley's binders, to be bound in the usual way, and I think to some others. Simpson was out on bail; I believe there were some impressions exhibited by the resective proprietors.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1614">
                  HENRY 
                  BLOMFIELD
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1614" type="surname" value="BLOMFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1614" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1614" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the employ of 
               <persName id="t18291029-196-person1615">
                  Thomas 
                  Norton
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1615" type="surname" value="Norton"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1615" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1615" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             Longman and others. I went to Simpson's house, in Tottenham-court-road; he deals in books and prints - this was on the 19th of September; I saw him, and asked for some prints - he produced several portfolios, and I saw some impressions for the Gem and the Literary Souvenir for the coming year; the publishers of those works get them out about the end of October - I bought two of them at 6d. each, and asked if he had any more; he said he had had more, and might possibly have some in a week or two- I marked the two I bought - these are them; these letters at the bottom of the print are not put by the engraver, but by a person he sends them to - we receive them perfect - this one is "Jacob's Dream," published by Longman and Co., and this is</p>
               <p>"Saturday Night," published by Marshall.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. LEE. Q. When you went to the shop did you see any other prints of a similar description? A. No; I saw none in the window - I went into the back shop: they were in the port-folios, among others - no doubt persons buy a great many prints, and sell one print for more than they give for the whole; these are in the same state as I bought them, except my marking - one of them was soiled; when they are soiled they are of little value.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. What would the value of them be if not soiled? A.Perhaps 6d. or 1s., or 1s. 6d.; Simpson sells second-hand books - these could not be the engraver's proofs, because they have the letters to them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1616">
                  WILLIAM 
                  RUDOLPH
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1616" type="surname" value="RUDOLPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1616" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1616" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the service of Joseph Hogarth, who lives in Somer's-terrace; I went to Mr. Simpson's, at the corner of Howland-street, Tottenham-court-road: I asked him if he had any engravings for the annuals - he said he had, and I bought five of him; these are them - here is our "Holyday Time," two of "Saturday Night," one of "The Stolen Interview," and one "The Masquerade;" they have the letters to them - he took them from a shelf in the shop.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. I suppose he sold them in the usual way? A. Yes; I did not look whether any were exhibited about the wall or the window.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1617">
                  JOSEPH 
                  HOGARTH
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1617" type="surname" value="HOGARTH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1617" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1617" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a print colourer. On the 19th of September I went to Mr. Simpson's shop, and bought five prints of annuals and another; these are them - some of them are good prints: there may be one or two damaged or dirty - I gave 2s. for the five; I asked where he got them - he said from a girl who represented that she had been sent by her young mistress, and he supposed they were engravers' proofs.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined Q. Are they precisely in the same state as when you bought them? A. Yes, with the exception of my mark - it frequently happens that prints of considerable value at one time, are sold at another, at a very small price.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1618">
                  WILLIAM 
                  MARSHALL
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1618" type="surname" value="MARSHALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1618" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1618" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a bookseller, and live in Middle-row. I publish the Gem; I gave the steel plates to Mr. Triggs, to have engravings struck off. On the 21st of September I went to Simpson's house, and bought three or four prints, for which I gave 6d. each - these are them - I did not see Simpson; these prints have been rumpled a little.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Where did you get them? A. This one from the window, and some of them from a portfolio; I was in the back shop - persons passing by might have seen this one in the window. The Gem has twelve prints in it, and we sell the book at 12s. - we charge the trade 7s. for the set.</p>
               <p>MR. BOLLAND. Q. Do the prints vary in value? A. Yes; the plates cost from one hundred to one hundred and eighty guineas a piece - these prints are worth 1s. or 1s. 6d. each.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1619">
                  THOMAS 
                  ANDREWS
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1619" type="surname" value="ANDREWS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1619" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1619" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the employ of 
               <persName id="t18291029-196-person1620">
                  Frederick 
                  Westley
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1620" type="surname" value="Westley"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1620" type="given" value="Frederick"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1620" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and Davis - they live in Stationer's-court, and are the publishers of the Juvenile Forget Me Not, and are part proprietors. I went to Mr. Simpson's on the 22nd of September - I saw him, and asked if he had any prints for a scrap-book; he said, "Yes, walk in" and shewed me two,"The Schoolmaster" and "The Masquerade;" I bought"The Schoolmaster" for 7d. - he had asked 8d. for it; I offered him 6d. - he said he could not take less than 8d., unless I took a number of them, as they were prints not yet published, and he had to pay a good price for them; he said some persons bought the books, and cut the plates out, but they got theirs in a different way - these are the prints.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. From where were they produced? A. From a shelf in the back shop - he did not state that he got them at a public auction; I did not ask where he got them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1621">
                  HENRY 
                  RICHARD BUCKERIDGE
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1621" type="surname" value="RICHARD BUCKERIDGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1621" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1621" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 23rd of September I went with a search-warrant, and took Simpson -I got five prints, which I left with Hewitt.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q.Where were they? A.Three of them in the window, and two on a shelf; he said I might search, and did not attempt to escape.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182910290079"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1622">
                  JANE 
                  BAIN
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1622" type="surname" value="BAIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1622" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1622" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I married the female prisoner's father, and live at No.30, London-street, Tottenham-court-road; she brought me some prints about the 15th of September: I did not count how many - there might be a dozen and a half or two dozen; she said she brought them for Tommy, a little boy, I have to nurse - I put them into a press, and kept them till the Thursday or Friday, and being very much distressed for money to buy food, I went to the corner of Howland-street, and saw Mr. Simpson - I asked if he would have the goodness to buy these prints; he said they were of little or no value to him, and he did not care about purchasing them; I begged of him to purchase them, and said I wanted 6d., or at least a few pence - he gave me 6d.; I think these are the prints - they were this kind; I begged him to give me two back, which he did, and they were taken out of my press by the officer; there was a gentleman in Mr. Simpson's parlour at the time - he did ask how I came by them; I said my husband's daughter had given them to me, and I supposed her mistress or master had given them to her.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. I believe she gave them to you for the child? A. Yes, but I had not given them to the child; Mr. Simpson did appear to be engaged, and refused to take them at all, but by my begging him he took them, and gave me two back; I believe there was only one person in his shop - he just pulled them asunder, and looked at them; he seemed anxious to go into the back shop.</p>


               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1623">
                  JAMES 
                  BRADSHAW
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1623" type="surname" value="BRADSHAW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1623" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1623" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. I went with Mr. Simpson to the last witness; I found these two prints there - I searched the box of the female prisoner at Mr. Triggs', and found these twenty-six prints there - Mr. Triggs was present.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. It was through Simpson you found her? A. Yes; he said he had found the old wretch who sold them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1624">
                  CHARLOTTE 
                  TRIGGS
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1624" type="surname" value="TRIGGS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1624" type="given" value="CHARLOTTE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1624" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Henry Triggs; I was present when the female prisoner's box was searched - it was in the same state that it had been before.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-196-person1625">
                  HENRY 
                  TRIGGS
               <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1625" type="surname" value="TRIGGS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1625" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-person1625" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . To the best of my belief these prints were all under my care, and were mine.</p>
               <p>Prisoner Bain. I leave it to the mercy of the Jury.</p>
               <p>Simpson's Defence. I leave it entirely to my Counsel.</p>
               <p>BAIN - <rs id="t18291029-196-verdict1105" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18291029-196-verdict1105" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 37.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18291029-196-punish1106" type="punishmentDescription">
